  "prompt": "How will I recover my Gmail if I forgot my password and I lost my phone recovery?",
  "response": "If you've forgotten your Gmail password and do not have access to your recovery phone, you can try the following steps to recover your account:\n\n1. **Visit the Google Account Recovery Page**: Go to the Google Account Recovery page (https://accounts.google.com/signin/recovery) and enter your email address.\n\n2. **Click on 'Forgot password?'**: Follow the instructions. You will be prompted to try the last password you remember. If you don't remember, click \"Try a different question.\"\n\n3. **Check Alternate Email**: If you have an alternate email address associated with your account, Google might send a verification code there. Follow the instructions in the email.\n\n4. **Answer Security Questions**: You may be asked some questions you set up when you created the account. Answer them as accurately as possible.\n\n5. **Provide Other Information**: You may need to provide additional information, such as when you created your account or who you email frequently, to verify your identity.\n\n6. **Review Recent Activity**: If Google prompts you to review recent activity, it could help in verifying your identity if you can recognize and confirm the log-in attempts and devices.\n\n7. **Consult the Google Help Center**: If you're unable to recover access via these routes, consult Google's Help Center. There might be additional methods available or updated steps to follow.\n\n8. **Consider Account Recovery Tools**: Google sometimes updates its recovery tools, so check for any new or updated recovery options in your Account settings, if you can access them, from other devices you are signed into.\n\n9. **Wait and Retry**: If you're locked out, sometimes waiting 24-48 hours can help as Google's automated systems may offer additional verification steps over time.\n\nFor future safety, make sure to update your recovery information once you regain access, including recovery phone and email, and consider setting up 2-Step Verification for added security.",
